  "Question": "<p>First of all I'd like to say that I have looked for the answers to my specific question and have not found it in the existing topics.</p> <p>The question is fairly simple. Say, we need to  prove statement P by the method of contradiction. <strong>Assuming</strong> that <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_292\"><?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"UTF-8\"?> <math alttext=\"\\lnot P\" display=\"block\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"> <mrow> <mi mathvariant=\"normal\">\u00ac</mi> <mo>\u2062</mo> <mi>P</mi> </mrow> </math></span> holds, using the list of statements proven earlier to hold or derived by us during the proof, we arrive to P being <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_293\"><?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"UTF-8\"?> <math alttext=\"true\" display=\"block\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"> <mrow> <mi>t</mi> <mo>\u2062</mo> <mi>r</mi> <mo>\u2062</mo> <mi>u</mi> <mo>\u2062</mo> <mi>e</mi> </mrow> </math></span>.</p> <p><span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_294\"><?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"UTF-8\"?> <math alttext=\"\\lnot P\\to A_{1}\\to\\ ...\\ \\to A_{n}\\to P\" display=\"block\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"> <mrow> <mrow> <mi mathvariant=\"normal\">\u00ac</mi> <mo>\u2062</mo> <mi>P</mi> </mrow> <mo>\u2192</mo> <msub> <mi>A</mi> <mn>1</mn> </msub> <mo rspace=\"7.5pt\">\u2192</mo> <mpadded width=\"+5pt\"> <mi mathvariant=\"normal\">\u2026</mi> </mpadded> <mo>\u2192</mo> <msub> <mi>A</mi> <mi>n</mi> </msub> <mo>\u2192</mo> <mi>P</mi> </mrow> </math></span> <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_295\"><?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"UTF-8\"?> <math alttext=\"\\lnot P\\to P\\iff\\lnot(\\lnot P)\\lor P\\iff P\" display=\"block\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"> <mrow> <mrow> <mrow> <mi mathvariant=\"normal\">\u00ac</mi> <mo>\u2062</mo> <mi>P</mi> </mrow> <mo>\u2192</mo> <mi>P</mi> </mrow> <mo>\u21d4</mo> <mrow> <mrow> <mi mathvariant=\"normal\">\u00ac</mi> <mo>\u2061</mo> <mrow> <mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo> <mrow> <mi mathvariant=\"normal\">\u00ac</mi> <mo>\u2062</mo> <mi>P</mi> </mrow> <mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo> </mrow> </mrow> <mo>\u2228</mo> <mi>P</mi> </mrow> <mo>\u21d4</mo> <mi>P</mi> </mrow> </math></span></p> <p>We can therefore add P to the list of our proven statements, because it was derived. Most of the proofs contain something in the lines of \"<em>the obtained contradiction proves that our initial assumption (<span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_296\"><?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"UTF-8\"?> <math alttext=\"\\lnot P\" display=\"block\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"> <mrow> <mi mathvariant=\"normal\">\u00ac</mi> <mo>\u2062</mo> <mi>P</mi> </mrow> </math></span>) was wrong</em> and so <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_297\"><?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"UTF-8\"?> <math alttext=\"P\" display=\"block\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"> <mi>P</mi> </math></span> holds\".</p> <p>What I don't understand is, if the initial assumption (<span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_298\"><?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"UTF-8\"?> <math alttext=\"\\lnot P\" display=\"block\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"> <mrow> <mi mathvariant=\"normal\">\u00ac</mi> <mo>\u2062</mo> <mi>P</mi> </mrow> </math></span>) is thus proven to be <em>false</em>, then why can we be sure that anything derived from it holds (in particular, that P holds)? On the other hand, if it cannot be derived then the assumption (<span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_299\"><?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"UTF-8\"?> <math alttext=\"\\lnot P\" display=\"block\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"> <mrow> <mi mathvariant=\"normal\">\u00ac</mi> <mo>\u2062</mo> <mi>P</mi> </mrow> </math></span>) can in fact be true. </p> <p>Can someone explain why this type of argument cannot be used?</p>",
  "Title": "Proof by contradiction, status of initial assumption after the proof is complete.",
  "Tags": "logic,proof-writing"
}